    <string name="article_body">World leaders gathered in Geneva this week have agreed to a landmark carbon reduction treaty that promises to reshape global climate policy for the next three decades. The agreement, signed by representatives of 147 nations, sets ambitious targets for reducing greenhouse gas emissions and establishes a new international fund to support developing nations in their transition to clean energy. Analysts are calling this the most significant environmental accord since the Paris Agreement. The deal came after five days of intense negotiations, with key sticking points resolved in a final marathon session that lasted through the night. Scientists and environmental groups have welcomed the accord, though some critics argue the targets do not go far enough.</string>
